<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-285-989  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 285 989.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  Dec 14 1989 v37 n25 p46(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber-optic links hold the key to the fast LANs of the future.andO;(Fiber Distributed Data Interface implements 100M-bit-per-secondlocal area networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Parker, Karen; Kaufman, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI) standard specifies atoken-passing, dual counter-rotating ring, 100M-bit-per-secondfiber-optic local-area network (LAN).andP;  Its forthcoming approval asan ANSI standard reflects the need for ever-faster data transferrates to complement faster and more powerful computers.andP;  FDDIoffers better reliability than other network architectures and cansupport hundreds of nodes and networks (such as Ethernet LANs)over substantial distances.andP;  The FDDI specifications conform tothe layered Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) model.andP;  Conformanceto OSI Layer 1, consisting of a physical layer defining theoptical hardware and physical medium-dependent layer defining theencoding and decoding mechanisms, is described.andP;  Other FDDIfeatures and functioning are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Optical CommunicationsLocal Area NetworksPerformance ImprovementStandardsFiber Distributed Data Interface StandardTransmission SpeedData Transfer Rate.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   FDDI physical layer defines optical cable, connectors andtransceivers. (chart)Media interface connector receptacle. (chart)The encoding and decoding techniques used to transmit data.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>